dataSets.name: Cutaneous Leishmaniasis - ACL/ZCL - Detailed aggregated - Annual
dataSets.description: This dataset captures the minimum aggregated data recommended to be collected by high burden countries for anthroponotic/zoonotic cutaneous leishmaniasis, on an annual basis.

dataElements.name: ZCL_GEN_EPID_new focus
dataElements.description:
A focus is defined and circumscribed geographical implementation unit (Region, district, village) containing the epidemiological factors needed for transmission : 
-	a human community, 
-	a source of infection, 
-	a competent vector population , 
-	and appropriate environmental conditions. 
In practice for surveillance purposes, a focus is a defined and circumscribed geographical implementation unit where there is evidence that locally acquired confirmed cases have been reported even if the transmission cycle has not been described.

A new focus is defined as a focus where leishmaniasis transmission was never reported previously.
dataElements.formName: How many new foci of zoonotic cutaneous leishmaniasis (ZCL) have been detected that reporting year?

dataElements.name: CL_GEN_Surv_Type
dataElements.description:
Please indicate the type of surveillance for CL that is present in your country. 
-Integrated means that leishmaniasis is part of an integrated disease surveillance system 
-Vertical means that leishmaniasis programme is running a specific surveillance system for CL or for leishmaniasis
dataElements.formName: What is the type of surveillance for CL?

dataElements.name: ZCL_GEN_EPID_outbreak
dataElements.description: WHO defines a disease outbreak as the occurrence of cases of disease in excess of what would normally be expected in a defined community, geographical area or season. An outbreak may occur in a restricted geographical area or may extend over several countries. It may last for a few days or weeks, or for several years. A single case of a communicable disease long absent from a population, or caused by an agent not previously recognized in that community or area, or the emergence of a previously unknown disease, may also constitute an outbreak and should be reported and investigated.
dataElements.formName: Was there any zoonotic cutaneous leishmaniasis (ZCL) outbreak over this reporting year?

1. EPIDEMIOLOGY

Case definitions

Probable ACL case: WHO defines a probable case of anthroponotic cutaneous leishmaniasis (ACL) as a person living in or having travelled to ACL-endemic areas showing typical CL skin lesions (macula, plaque, nodule, ulcer).

Confirmed ACL case

  • Lab-Confirmed ACL case: WHO defines a lab-confirmed case of anthroponotic cutaneous leishmaniasis (ACL) as a probable case of ACL with parasitological confirmation of the diagnosis (positive smear or culture or PCR).
  • OR Clinically-Confirmed ACL case: WHO defines a clinically-confirmed case of anthroponotic cutaneous leishmaniasis (ACL) as a probable ACL case which has not been confirmed by laboratory (test not done or negative), but the clinician decides on clinical grounds that the case is clinically confirmed.

1.1 Confirmed ACL Cases (either laboratory or clinically), by Type

Relapse: WHO defines a relapse as an ACL case who experiences recurrence of typical ACL lesions with parasitological confirmation at any time point after cure.

• Death: any death, whether or not related to ACL.
